WEBVTT

00:05.887 --> 00:07.149
[Claire] Previously...

00:07.280 --> 00:08.542
Been drinking
more than usual lately.

00:08.629 --> 00:10.283
He's taken a notion

00:10.413 --> 00:11.588
that he should have been there
to defend us.

00:11.675 --> 00:12.981
That bastard.

00:13.112 --> 00:13.895
I'm fine.

00:13.982 --> 00:15.375
[gasps]

00:15.505 --> 00:17.116
[tense music plays]

00:17.246 --> 00:18.552
[sighs]

00:18.639 --> 00:20.989
Lift your skirts.

00:21.120 --> 00:22.860
Damn hand!

00:22.991 --> 00:24.210
[grunts]

00:24.340 --> 00:25.820
I have considered the matter,

00:25.950 --> 00:29.389
and I will undergo
your... operation.

00:29.519 --> 00:30.825
What am I gonna do without you,

00:30.912 --> 00:32.087
with another bairn coming?

00:32.174 --> 00:33.958
[groaning]

00:34.089 --> 00:36.222
-Un nain.
-What did he say?

00:36.352 --> 00:37.223
Means he's a dwarf.

00:37.353 --> 00:39.094
He's beautiful.

00:39.225 --> 00:41.053
[Jamie] Amy McCallum's husband
died a month ago,

00:41.183 --> 00:43.490
and she was left
with two young bairns.

00:43.620 --> 00:45.622
So you decided to pass along

00:45.753 --> 00:47.102
Chief Byrd's
request for weapons.

00:47.189 --> 00:48.930
I'm recommending
we do as they ask.

00:49.061 --> 00:50.671
The Cherokee
will have their guns.

00:51.367 --> 00:53.587
[man] ♪ Sing me a song ♪

00:53.761 --> 00:56.677
♪ Of a lad that is gone ♪

00:56.851 --> 00:59.201
♪ Say, could that lad ♪

00:59.288 --> 01:02.117
♪ Be I? ♪

01:02.291 --> 01:04.380
♪ Merry of soul ♪

01:04.554 --> 01:07.296
♪ He sailed on a day ♪

01:07.470 --> 01:09.690
♪ Over the sea ♪

01:09.864 --> 01:12.780
♪ To Skye ♪

01:12.954 --> 01:15.304
[woman] ♪ Billow and breeze ♪

01:15.478 --> 01:17.872
♪ Islands and seas ♪

01:18.046 --> 01:23.704
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

01:23.878 --> 01:25.793
-[man] ♪ All that was good ♪
-[woman] ♪ All that was good ♪

01:25.967 --> 01:28.404
[man] ♪ All that was fair ♪

01:28.491 --> 01:30.450
[both] ♪ All that was me ♪

01:30.624 --> 01:33.496
♪ Is gone ♪

01:33.670 --> 01:35.803
♪ Sing me a song ♪

01:35.977 --> 01:38.762
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

01:38.936 --> 01:40.938
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

01:41.113 --> 01:43.898
♪ Be I? ♪

01:44.072 --> 01:46.118
♪ Merry of soul ♪

01:46.205 --> 01:49.164
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

01:49.338 --> 01:53.125
♪ Over the sea ♪

01:53.299 --> 01:59.305
♪ To Skye ♪

01:59.740 --> 02:02.612
[dramatic music plays]

02:02.786 --> 02:05.528
♪ ♪

02:07.617 --> 02:10.359
[man singing in Gaelic]

02:10.533 --> 02:13.275
♪ ♪

02:24.068 --> 02:26.854
[dramatic music plays]

02:27.028 --> 02:29.813
♪ ♪

02:32.425 --> 02:35.210
[baby crying]

02:35.384 --> 02:37.952
♪ ♪

02:38.866 --> 02:41.129
[grunts]

02:41.260 --> 02:42.783
-[baby crying]
-[boy 1] There he goes!

02:42.913 --> 02:45.133
-Hurry up!
-[boy 2] He's floating.

02:45.264 --> 02:48.180
-[boy 1] He's floating!
-[boy 3] Come on!

02:48.310 --> 02:49.572
He's headed for the rapids!

02:49.703 --> 02:50.834
[boy 4] There he goes!

02:51.008 --> 02:53.750
♪ ♪

02:56.188 --> 02:59.103
[baby crying]

02:59.191 --> 03:00.931
♪ ♪

03:01.062 --> 03:03.412
Oh! It's Mr. MacKenzie!

03:03.586 --> 03:06.328
♪ ♪

03:24.172 --> 03:25.086
[boy 1] There they are!

03:27.654 --> 03:29.308
Come on!
We'll catch them this way!

03:29.438 --> 03:30.439
[boy 2] Oh, no!

03:30.613 --> 03:31.527
♪ ♪

03:31.658 --> 03:32.963
Wait for me!

03:33.137 --> 03:34.748
♪ ♪

03:34.878 --> 03:36.053
The basket!

03:36.184 --> 03:37.925
[boy 4] Look!
There's the basket!

03:38.099 --> 03:41.189
♪ ♪

03:41.320 --> 03:42.495
[boy 1] Oh, no! The waterfall!

03:42.582 --> 03:45.367
♪ ♪

03:49.980 --> 03:51.417
[Roger panting]

03:51.547 --> 03:53.375
Right, ye wee bastards!

03:53.506 --> 03:54.855
Whose idea was this?

03:54.985 --> 03:56.552
[baby crying]

03:56.683 --> 03:57.597
Don't you dare run!

04:00.034 --> 04:02.166
You shouldna touch him, sir.
You'll burn yourself.

04:02.297 --> 04:03.994
Yeah.

04:04.081 --> 04:06.127
They wanted to see
if he'd float.

04:06.258 --> 04:08.129
And he did; that must mean
he's the devil's seed.

04:08.216 --> 04:10.523
Ma and Da said so.

04:10.653 --> 04:12.525
He floated
because he was in a basket.

04:12.612 --> 04:15.354
♪ ♪

04:15.484 --> 04:18.226
I baptize thee Henri-Christian.

04:18.357 --> 04:20.054
[baby crying]

04:20.141 --> 04:22.404
In the name of the Father
and the Son

04:22.535 --> 04:23.927
and the Holy Ghost.

04:25.886 --> 04:27.583
You hear that?

04:27.714 --> 04:29.585
His name's Christian.

04:29.672 --> 04:32.240
He belongs to the Lord.

04:32.371 --> 04:34.460
You trouble him again,
and Satan'll pop up

04:34.547 --> 04:36.679
and drag you straight down
screaming to hell!

04:36.810 --> 04:38.681
[solemn music plays]

04:38.812 --> 04:39.769
Germain!

04:39.943 --> 04:42.772
♪ ♪

04:54.393 --> 04:57.134
Well, he's safe and dry
and sleeping.

04:59.746 --> 05:01.487
He wasn't hurt.

05:01.617 --> 05:03.706
All is well, then.

05:03.837 --> 05:05.752
"Well?"

05:05.882 --> 05:08.189
I should drown
the lot of them in a well.

05:09.016 --> 05:12.193
If they'd harmed a hair
on his wee head...

05:14.021 --> 05:15.501
And you.

05:15.631 --> 05:17.590
I turn my back for one moment.

05:17.720 --> 05:19.940
I thought he was safe,
sleeping in his basket,

05:20.070 --> 05:21.289
-and you were just--
-It was a test.

05:23.160 --> 05:24.379
Seems their parents
told them that children

05:24.510 --> 05:26.816
like Henri-Christian are...

05:26.947 --> 05:29.123
a demon-born,

05:29.253 --> 05:31.647
that the water rejects
their wickedness.

05:31.778 --> 05:33.257
Thank God they didn't try

05:33.345 --> 05:35.129
to take him
out of his basket, then.

05:35.259 --> 05:36.435
They were afraid to touch him.

05:37.914 --> 05:39.481
They thought he'd burn them.

05:39.612 --> 05:41.222
And you believed this?

05:41.309 --> 05:43.398
You think your brother
is a demon?

05:43.529 --> 05:45.357
I thought they'd
leave us alone.

05:45.487 --> 05:47.271
Oh, you know better than that!

05:47.402 --> 05:49.230
-[baby crying]
-Oh, just...

05:53.147 --> 05:54.931
[door slams]

05:55.062 --> 05:55.932
I'll talk to them.

05:59.893 --> 06:01.590
Fergus,
don't let it bother you.

06:04.854 --> 06:05.594
[door slams]

06:11.513 --> 06:14.211
Find your associates.

06:14.342 --> 06:17.519
Tell them they're expected
in my parlor before supper

06:17.650 --> 06:19.216
to receive a punishment.

06:22.437 --> 06:23.873
I'll go with you, lad.

06:32.534 --> 06:33.405
Fergus.

06:44.546 --> 06:46.679
In the mountain villages
of France,

06:46.809 --> 06:48.724
a dwarf child would be left
for the wolves.

06:50.291 --> 06:51.988
We wouldn't let that happen
here.

06:54.164 --> 06:57.733
We'll surround Henri-Christian
with love,

06:57.864 --> 06:59.996
protect him,

07:00.083 --> 07:03.260
and make sure he gets treated
like everyone else

07:03.391 --> 07:05.219
so he'll grow up happy and--

07:05.349 --> 07:06.350
And after he's grown?

07:08.004 --> 07:09.310
Will he have a happy life?

07:10.833 --> 07:11.878
Marry?

07:13.488 --> 07:14.881
Provide for a family?

07:15.011 --> 07:17.840
I don't see why he couldn't...

07:17.971 --> 07:19.973
or why he can't be educated

07:20.103 --> 07:21.496
or learn a trade,

07:21.627 --> 07:23.498
be able to work at something.

07:23.585 --> 07:25.587
Ah.

07:25.718 --> 07:26.893
Something.

07:30.418 --> 07:31.463
[sighs]

07:31.593 --> 07:32.942
With respect, milady,

07:33.029 --> 07:35.075
you have never seen
the life of a dwarf.

07:35.205 --> 07:36.511
And you have?

07:38.252 --> 07:40.210
Oui...

07:40.341 --> 07:42.909
à Paris.

07:43.039 --> 07:46.652
The house itself had girls,
of course, and even children.

07:46.782 --> 07:48.697
They were the bread and butter
of the establishment.

07:51.091 --> 07:54.007
But there are always those
who desire the exotic...

07:54.094 --> 07:56.662
and who will pay.

07:56.792 --> 07:59.229
So every now and then,
the Madame

07:59.316 --> 08:02.581
would send for those
who dealt in such things,

08:02.711 --> 08:04.452
Le Maître des Champignons.

08:04.583 --> 08:06.498
The Master of Mushrooms?

08:08.587 --> 08:10.023
The Dwarf Master.

08:11.372 --> 08:13.069
[chuckles]

08:13.200 --> 08:15.550
Les chanterelles,
we called them, the females.

08:17.552 --> 08:22.296
The male,
they were les morilles...

08:22.426 --> 08:24.820
exotic delicacies
valued for the rarity

08:24.907 --> 08:26.518
of their twisted shapes...

08:28.998 --> 08:31.218
...the strange savor
of their flesh.

08:34.874 --> 08:36.397
But they were not
badly treated, les champignons.

08:36.528 --> 08:37.529
They were of value.

08:40.183 --> 08:43.404
The master would buy
such infants from their parents

08:43.491 --> 08:45.754
or collect them
from the streets.

08:47.147 --> 08:49.323
I knew one of them quite well.

08:49.453 --> 08:52.195
Luc, he was called.

08:52.282 --> 08:55.285
We'd sometimes work together,

08:55.416 --> 08:57.070
pickpocketing
wealthy customers.

09:02.292 --> 09:06.035
I found him one day
in the alley...

09:06.166 --> 09:08.734
with his throat cut.

09:11.519 --> 09:15.436
So the Madame sent the doorkeep
to fetch the body

09:15.567 --> 09:17.394
and sold it to a physician...

09:17.481 --> 09:19.222
[somber music plays]

09:19.353 --> 09:22.008
...to cut them up, to sell
their parts for divination.

09:22.095 --> 09:24.532
♪ ♪

09:24.663 --> 09:26.534
I'm so sorry, Fergus.

09:26.621 --> 09:29.493
When I met you and milord,

09:29.624 --> 09:32.018
I found a world
beyond a brothel

09:32.105 --> 09:34.237
and vowed never to return
to such a place.

09:34.411 --> 09:37.110
♪ ♪

09:37.240 --> 09:41.636
That my son might find himself
in such a life...

09:41.767 --> 09:45.597
You can't think
that Jamie or I,

09:45.684 --> 09:48.295
that-that we would allow
such a thing to happen.

09:48.425 --> 09:51.603
No, you will not, milady,
but you will not live forever,

09:51.733 --> 09:54.823
nor will milord nor I.

09:54.954 --> 09:56.608
But the child
will be a dwarf forever,

09:56.695 --> 09:58.653
and that's my fault.

09:58.784 --> 09:59.959
I wasn't there
to protect my wife,

10:00.089 --> 10:02.265
and he was beaten in the womb.

10:02.396 --> 10:06.356
His condition has nothing
to do with what happened.

10:06.487 --> 10:08.707
You have to believe me,
Fergus.

10:08.794 --> 10:10.360
It wasn't your fault.

10:10.447 --> 10:13.102
I'm a physician. I know.

10:13.189 --> 10:14.451
♪ ♪

10:14.582 --> 10:17.324
Fergus! Fergus!

10:17.498 --> 10:20.240
♪ ♪

10:31.468 --> 10:33.296
Mr. Christie.

10:34.036 --> 10:36.473
I've been waiting
for some time.

10:36.560 --> 10:38.911
Wasn't sure how long you'd be.

10:39.041 --> 10:41.783
Some of the youngsters
put my grandson in the river

10:41.914 --> 10:42.741
to see if he would float.

10:44.351 --> 10:45.395
You know,
I hope you've not been

10:45.526 --> 10:48.094
encouraging
this kind of nonsense.

10:48.224 --> 10:50.574
Mistress Fraser,
I assure you I have not.

10:52.446 --> 10:54.404
I am an educated man.

10:54.535 --> 10:57.451
I'm sorry
that such a thing occurred.

10:57.581 --> 10:59.235
Is the child well?

11:00.454 --> 11:01.411
For now.

11:01.542 --> 11:03.631
Well...

11:03.762 --> 11:05.807
I'll speak to the boys
and their parents.

11:05.938 --> 11:07.809
They know I disapprove
of superstitions.

11:07.940 --> 11:09.419
It's all right.

11:09.506 --> 11:10.943
My husband's handling
the matter.

11:14.076 --> 11:15.121
[sighs] How can I help you?

11:16.992 --> 11:18.777
It's been long enough.

11:18.864 --> 11:20.256
My other hand is healed.

11:21.257 --> 11:21.997
It is time.

11:25.871 --> 11:27.394
Well, good.

11:27.524 --> 11:28.525
Well, come inside.

11:31.137 --> 11:33.095
I'll prepare the surgery
and the ether.

11:33.226 --> 11:35.271
Ether?

11:35.358 --> 11:37.186
I have agreed to the operation,

11:37.317 --> 11:40.537
but I will not allow you
to employ your potions upon me.

11:41.625 --> 11:43.497
Well, why not?

11:43.627 --> 11:45.629
It is the devil's work
to use such--

11:45.760 --> 11:49.024
I thought just Highlanders
were stubborn as rocks.

11:50.896 --> 11:52.767
Stubborn as rocks?

11:52.898 --> 11:54.203
-Mr. Christie is refusing to--
-Mistress Fraser insists--

11:55.074 --> 11:57.206
God wants him
to have the surgery,

11:57.293 --> 11:58.730
but the masochist
is refusing the ether.

11:58.860 --> 12:00.209
"Masochist"?

12:00.340 --> 12:01.689
Well, it's a word for...

12:03.822 --> 12:05.432
...people who prefer
to suffer pain.

12:08.652 --> 12:10.916
You always were
an awkward bugger, Tom.

12:11.046 --> 12:13.701
Ye must do as you please.

12:13.788 --> 12:15.659
I can tell you from experience,
it does hurt a great deal.

12:17.792 --> 12:19.402
She means to cut
into your hand.

12:20.969 --> 12:23.363
-I know that.
-Aye.

12:23.493 --> 12:25.234
But you have no notion
what that's like.

12:25.365 --> 12:27.628
I have.

12:27.759 --> 12:29.891
Claire healed my hand
years ago.

12:30.022 --> 12:31.893
Hurt like the devil.

12:32.024 --> 12:32.851
Hardly shows now.

12:34.722 --> 12:37.377
You don't want to suffer
like that

12:37.507 --> 12:39.379
if there's a choice about it,
and there is.

12:42.425 --> 12:44.732
And I have made my choice.

13:05.057 --> 13:06.101
Please dinna tell my ma.

13:08.277 --> 13:10.453
I'm not here to speak
to your mother, Aiden.

13:10.584 --> 13:12.281
My business is with you.

13:13.369 --> 13:14.762
Mr. Fraser wants you and your
friends from this morning

13:14.893 --> 13:16.416
to come to see him
before supper.

13:18.374 --> 13:21.247
Otherwise, he'll come round.

13:21.377 --> 13:23.118
He will talk to your mother.

13:24.163 --> 13:24.903
[Amy screams]

13:26.905 --> 13:28.558
-Stay with Aiden.
-[Amy screams]

13:32.998 --> 13:34.651
Mistress McCallum!

13:34.782 --> 13:36.784
Oh, thank you, dear Lord.
You sent the minister.

13:36.915 --> 13:38.568
What?

13:38.699 --> 13:41.180
I'm not exactly that, you know.

13:41.310 --> 13:43.704
Aye.
Well, maybe not exactly, sir,

13:43.835 --> 13:47.534
but we enjoyed your sermon
this past week, and...

13:47.664 --> 13:49.275
please, can you help?

13:49.928 --> 13:53.279
Lizzie Wemyss
brought me some milk.

13:53.409 --> 13:56.717
I went to dip a bit out
for Aiden, but...

13:56.848 --> 13:57.979
well, if it's no' a devil
that's got into it,

13:58.110 --> 13:59.763
it's something else.

13:59.894 --> 14:01.635
It's haunted, sir,
I'm sure of it.

14:03.071 --> 14:03.811
[Roger clears throat]

14:10.165 --> 14:11.253
-[low croak]
-[gasps]

14:11.384 --> 14:12.733
Oh!

14:12.864 --> 14:14.735
[breathing shakily]

14:14.866 --> 14:16.780
[chuckles]

14:18.957 --> 14:20.567
-It's just a wee bullfrog.
-[croaks]

14:20.697 --> 14:22.308
Well, not exactly wee.

14:22.395 --> 14:23.613
But he's friendly.

14:25.050 --> 14:26.878
[bullfrog croaks]

14:32.448 --> 14:36.017
Miss Wemyss watches over
a number of lads on the ridge.

14:36.148 --> 14:37.845
My guess is, one of them
was playing a trick.

14:37.976 --> 14:41.153
[cries, sniffles]

14:41.283 --> 14:42.023
Why?

14:44.112 --> 14:45.679
Why has God brought me here?

14:45.809 --> 14:48.769
Well, we must trust...

14:48.900 --> 14:51.337
[solemn music plays]

14:51.467 --> 14:53.469
...that He has a plan
of some sort...

14:53.643 --> 14:56.646
♪ ♪

14:56.777 --> 14:58.648
...even if we don't know
what it is.

14:58.779 --> 15:00.172
[scoffs]

15:00.302 --> 15:02.304
To bring us all
to this terrible place...

15:02.478 --> 15:04.741
♪ ♪

15:04.872 --> 15:07.440
...take my husband from me,
and leave me to starve?

15:08.223 --> 15:11.444
It's not such a terrible place.

15:11.574 --> 15:13.011
And it doesn't rain
as much as it does in Scotland.

15:13.141 --> 15:15.578
[laughs, sniffs]

15:15.752 --> 15:18.494
♪ ♪

15:20.496 --> 15:22.585
I'll never see it again...

15:22.716 --> 15:25.284
Scotland...

15:25.414 --> 15:26.372
will I?

15:27.329 --> 15:30.115
I can't say.

15:30.245 --> 15:33.031
But I won't let you starve.

15:33.118 --> 15:34.946
That's all I can promise you,
but I do promise it.

15:35.120 --> 15:37.949
♪ ♪

15:38.079 --> 15:38.950
[exhales shakily]

15:39.080 --> 15:41.778
[wheel rattling]

15:41.909 --> 15:44.520
Oh, this is wonderful!

15:45.739 --> 15:47.045
It's a muckle wheel.

15:49.090 --> 15:50.309
I'll be better
with some practice.

15:51.919 --> 15:54.922
You made this?

15:55.053 --> 15:56.924
Evan Lindsay helped.

15:57.055 --> 15:58.665
He knows which wood
works best.

15:58.795 --> 16:00.580
I'll work twice as fast.

16:00.710 --> 16:01.624
Then I'll have more time
for the bairns.

16:01.755 --> 16:03.191
[children clamoring]

16:03.322 --> 16:04.627
-[boy] No more!
-[toy thuds]

16:04.758 --> 16:07.108
Hey. Hey.

16:07.239 --> 16:08.936
No more fighting,

16:09.067 --> 16:10.720
or no more vroom
until tomorrow.

16:10.851 --> 16:11.808
Yes?

16:13.201 --> 16:14.550
Good boy. Go on.

16:18.554 --> 16:20.600
Why do you call them "vrooms"?

16:22.384 --> 16:25.083
Uh, it's a sound

16:25.213 --> 16:26.084
that Jem makes
when he's playing with them.

16:27.824 --> 16:29.783
I wonder if Roger's
having any luck

16:29.913 --> 16:31.785
rounding up the boys
from this morning.

16:34.005 --> 16:35.919
I'm not sure
what good it'll do.

16:36.050 --> 16:38.313
It's the parents
who need thrashing.

16:38.444 --> 16:42.361
I did expect them home by now.
Fergus too.

16:42.491 --> 16:46.147
I told Da we'd come round
with the bairn and Germain

16:46.278 --> 16:47.757
for whatever punishment
he'd thought up.

16:49.803 --> 16:50.760
And...

16:53.111 --> 16:55.635
Fergus promised me
he'd stop drinking.

16:58.899 --> 16:59.769
Good.

17:00.727 --> 17:02.207
[sighs]

17:02.337 --> 17:05.949
[solemn music plays]

17:06.080 --> 17:07.995
I'm sure Fergus
will be here soon.

17:08.126 --> 17:09.083
Yeah.

17:09.257 --> 17:11.651
♪ ♪

17:11.738 --> 17:13.522
It will get better.

17:13.609 --> 17:14.610
You'll see.

17:14.784 --> 17:17.700
♪ ♪

17:17.787 --> 17:20.442
[light suspenseful music plays]

17:20.616 --> 17:23.358
♪ ♪

17:32.976 --> 17:34.456
Thank you.

17:34.630 --> 17:37.372
♪ ♪

17:39.635 --> 17:40.810
Here.

17:41.942 --> 17:44.292
You might want to bite down
on this, for the pain.

17:45.946 --> 17:47.121
I'd rather say my prayers.

17:47.295 --> 17:50.081
♪ ♪

18:07.707 --> 18:08.490
[Tom clears throat]

18:08.664 --> 18:11.363
♪ ♪

18:14.017 --> 18:14.757
[clears throat]

18:17.151 --> 18:20.023
At your convenience then,
Mistress Fraser.

18:20.111 --> 18:22.939
[dramatic music plays]

18:23.026 --> 18:24.637
[screaming]

18:24.767 --> 18:26.160
-Hold still, man.
-Oh, God!

18:26.291 --> 18:27.901
Jamie, the bucket.

18:28.031 --> 18:30.077
[groaning]

18:30.164 --> 18:31.905
You may experience
some nausea, Mr. Christie,

18:32.035 --> 18:35.126
and if you do,
you can vomit there.

18:35.256 --> 18:37.084
[groaning]

18:37.215 --> 18:38.041
Shall I stop?

18:38.172 --> 18:39.565
No.

18:39.695 --> 18:41.567
A shame to waste
that much whisky.

18:41.741 --> 18:44.483
♪ ♪

18:47.442 --> 18:49.401
[groans]

18:49.531 --> 18:50.967
"The right hand
of the Lord is exalted."

18:51.098 --> 18:52.578
[Tom] Aye.

18:52.665 --> 18:55.537
"The right hand of the Lord
doeth valiantly."

18:55.668 --> 18:56.886
That's appropriate, no?

18:57.017 --> 18:58.627
Go on.

18:59.976 --> 19:02.501
"You shall not die, but live,

19:02.631 --> 19:04.764
"and declare
the works of the Lord.

19:04.894 --> 19:06.766
"The Lord
hath chastened me so,

19:06.853 --> 19:09.682
"but He hath not
given me over unto death.

19:09.769 --> 19:10.944
Open to me the gates..."

19:11.074 --> 19:12.467
[both] "Of righteousness.

19:12.598 --> 19:14.165
"I will praise thee.

19:14.295 --> 19:17.037
For thou hast heard me."

19:17.168 --> 19:19.387
-[Jamie] "God is the Lord..."
-[Tom] The Lord!

19:19.518 --> 19:20.649
"...which hath
showed us light."

19:20.780 --> 19:23.609
-Aye!
-"Bind the sacrifice with cords

19:23.739 --> 19:25.915
even unto the horns
of the altar."

19:26.046 --> 19:30.006
-[screams]
-You must not move.

19:30.137 --> 19:32.661
I need both my hands.
I can't hold yours.

19:32.792 --> 19:35.577
[Tom panting]

19:35.751 --> 19:37.666
♪ ♪

19:37.797 --> 19:38.841
[horse neighs]

19:38.972 --> 19:41.757
[Tom grunting]

19:41.888 --> 19:42.628
[clears throat]

19:45.544 --> 19:48.242
I was only coming to ask
Mistress Fraser something.

19:48.329 --> 19:50.026
Seeing as my father's in there.

19:50.157 --> 19:52.159
Well, all the more reason
to go in.

19:52.290 --> 19:53.116
Ye're Auntie Claire's
apprentice.

19:55.380 --> 19:56.772
She called me her apprentice?

19:56.859 --> 19:58.513
[laughs softly]

19:58.644 --> 19:59.601
Well, that's why you've
been hovering about here

19:59.732 --> 20:01.777
all the time, is it no'?

20:03.214 --> 20:04.040
To learn the ways of a healer?

20:04.911 --> 20:06.652
Yes.

20:06.782 --> 20:08.610
-[Tom screams]
-Don't let my father hear you.

20:08.741 --> 20:11.352
He doesn't like me
to see him suffer

20:11.483 --> 20:13.876
or to offend my delicate
female sensibilities.

20:15.051 --> 20:16.401
You seem strong enough

20:16.531 --> 20:17.967
to stand the sight
of a wee bit of blood.

20:18.098 --> 20:20.666
And you'd be helping
to make him well.

20:20.796 --> 20:23.451
He's more worried about
the health of my eternal soul.

20:23.582 --> 20:25.366
Prefers that I keep
my mind on that.

20:25.497 --> 20:28.064
Well, rather
than lingering out here

20:28.151 --> 20:29.718
like two souls in limbo...

20:31.981 --> 20:33.461
...I'll walk with you home?

20:34.288 --> 20:37.465
I'm not Catholic,
so my soul won't be in limbo.

20:37.552 --> 20:39.641
But yes, you may walk me home.

20:43.515 --> 20:46.169
[both]
"The Lord is my shepherd.

20:46.300 --> 20:48.215
"I shall not want.

20:48.346 --> 20:52.741
"He maketh me to lie down
in green pastures.

20:52.872 --> 20:56.223
"He leadeth me
beside the still waters.

20:56.354 --> 20:59.182
"Yea, though I walk

20:59.270 --> 21:02.055
"through the valley
of the shadow of death,

21:02.185 --> 21:06.364
I will fear no evil,
for thou art with me."

21:08.670 --> 21:11.673
"Surely goodness and mercy
shall follow me

21:11.804 --> 21:13.588
all the days of my life."

21:13.719 --> 21:14.372
[softly] Aye.

21:15.242 --> 21:17.766
Ah. Ooh.

21:17.897 --> 21:19.290
[Tom grunts softly]

21:24.556 --> 21:25.339
It worked.

21:27.907 --> 21:30.692
You'll have more motion
once the wound has healed

21:30.823 --> 21:32.477
and I've taken out the sutures,

21:32.607 --> 21:33.478
but yes, it worked.

21:36.350 --> 21:39.614
I would like you to stay here
overnight in the surgery

21:39.701 --> 21:41.007
so I can keep an eye on you.

21:41.094 --> 21:42.182
Aye.

21:43.749 --> 21:47.100
[dog barking]

21:47.230 --> 21:48.275
Why would your father
ever be worried

21:48.406 --> 21:51.452
about your eternal fate?

21:51.583 --> 21:53.585
I'm flattered
you don't think he should be.

21:53.715 --> 21:55.238
But why not?

21:55.369 --> 21:57.240
Are we not all sinners,
Mister...

21:58.503 --> 21:59.895
It is Fraser, isn't it?

22:00.026 --> 22:01.636
It's Murray.

22:01.767 --> 22:03.725
My ma's a Fraser.

22:03.856 --> 22:07.076
And aye, we are all sinners,
but...

22:07.207 --> 22:09.818
a young lass like yourself?

22:09.905 --> 22:11.951
Surely ye've done no wrong.

22:12.081 --> 22:13.648
-Looks can be deceiving.
-Mm.

22:17.260 --> 22:21.090
I suppose,
if my ma could see me,

22:21.221 --> 22:23.658
she'd be worried about
my eternal fate as well.

22:23.789 --> 22:26.400
[Malva] My mother was not
so spiritually inclined.

22:26.531 --> 22:28.576
[soft music plays]

22:28.707 --> 22:29.360
[Young Ian] What do you mean?

22:29.534 --> 22:31.797
♪ ♪

22:31.927 --> 22:33.364
She was hanged as a witch.

22:34.408 --> 22:36.105
Hanged?

22:36.236 --> 22:37.672
When?

22:37.803 --> 22:39.457
I was very young.

22:39.544 --> 22:40.893
I hardly remember.

22:40.980 --> 22:42.851
[child shouting]

22:42.982 --> 22:44.200
[somber music plays]

22:44.331 --> 22:45.593
I'm almost home now.

22:45.724 --> 22:47.465
My brother
will be home as well,

22:47.595 --> 22:50.250
and he'd not be pleased to see
me walking with a young man.

22:50.337 --> 22:51.947
Aye.

22:52.078 --> 22:53.862
Of course.

22:54.036 --> 22:56.778
♪ ♪

23:10.139 --> 23:13.055
'Tis my understanding...

23:13.186 --> 23:15.710
you wicked wee scoundrels

23:15.841 --> 23:19.845
were eager to play
with fire this morning.

23:22.500 --> 23:25.416
There, nice and hot.

23:28.854 --> 23:31.117
I've half a mind
to burn ye myself.

23:32.118 --> 23:36.557
Since you're growing men
who mean to learn by doing,

23:36.688 --> 23:38.820
there's a choice:

23:38.951 --> 23:41.736
touch the bairn...

23:41.867 --> 23:43.216
or the poker.

23:46.088 --> 23:47.742
Go on. Make yer choice.

23:50.528 --> 23:52.051
You go first.

23:52.181 --> 23:53.487
I dinna want to.

24:02.801 --> 24:06.718
[soft music plays]

24:06.848 --> 24:08.981
[Jamie]
He's a sweet lad, is he no'?

24:09.111 --> 24:10.504
Ye can see that he is.

24:10.678 --> 24:13.420
♪ ♪

24:19.731 --> 24:21.341
[baby laughs]

24:21.472 --> 24:24.170
See there, ye made him laugh.

24:24.300 --> 24:25.693
He likes you.

24:25.867 --> 24:28.566
♪ ♪

24:31.569 --> 24:34.049
[baby fussing]

24:34.180 --> 24:35.007
Good.

24:35.181 --> 24:37.923
♪ ♪

24:44.320 --> 24:47.976
See?
I told you he wasn't a demon.

24:48.063 --> 24:50.631
Is it true,
what Mr. MacKenzie said

24:50.762 --> 24:52.720
about the bairn
belonging to the Lord?

24:52.807 --> 24:54.287
I certainly wouldn't argue

24:54.417 --> 24:57.377
with what Mr. MacKenzie
said about that.

24:57.508 --> 25:00.641
But whoever else he belongs to,

25:00.728 --> 25:03.862
Henri-Christian belongs to me.

25:04.993 --> 25:07.126
Best you all remember it.

25:07.256 --> 25:09.563
[all] Aye, Mr. Fraser, sir.

25:10.869 --> 25:14.394
Now, help yourself to bread
and honey and be on yer way.

25:14.481 --> 25:17.266
♪ ♪

25:22.750 --> 25:25.405
Henri-Christian
also belongs to you, Germain.

25:25.579 --> 25:28.016
♪ ♪

25:32.891 --> 25:34.501
He's your wee brother.

25:35.633 --> 25:37.069
He needs your protection.

25:37.199 --> 25:38.853
You understand?

25:38.984 --> 25:40.376
Yes, Grandpère.

25:40.507 --> 25:42.857
[soft music plays]

25:42.988 --> 25:43.902
Go on.

25:44.076 --> 25:46.905
♪ ♪

25:46.992 --> 25:50.256
[baby cooing]

25:50.343 --> 25:52.780
♪ ♪

25:57.045 --> 26:01.136
[child] Papa, I'm so hungry.

26:01.223 --> 26:03.617
[indistinct chatter]

26:03.704 --> 26:04.575
Papa!

26:07.752 --> 26:09.667
-[baby coos]
-I'm really hungry.

26:12.539 --> 26:14.062
[Marsali] Shh, shh, shh.

26:14.193 --> 26:15.586
Dinna fash.
Your ma's here now.

26:16.717 --> 26:18.458
[child crying]

26:21.853 --> 26:23.463
Have ye been
neglecting the bairns?

26:29.338 --> 26:30.731
How much drink have ye had?

26:30.862 --> 26:32.515
If I'm still talking,
then not enough.

26:34.648 --> 26:35.562
Maybe I need another.

26:37.477 --> 26:39.087
You promised me ye wouldna.

26:47.443 --> 26:49.097
You're so much better
than this, my love.

26:53.101 --> 26:55.626
I've seen what drink'll do
to a man.

26:55.713 --> 26:57.889
I watched my mother
put up with it.

26:58.019 --> 26:59.194
Me and Joanie suffered
because of it.

27:01.196 --> 27:03.634
And so help me God,
I willna put up wi' it again.

27:06.375 --> 27:08.377
So please, Fergus...

27:11.119 --> 27:12.904
...tell me how to help ye,
please.

27:13.034 --> 27:15.471
You can't.

27:15.602 --> 27:18.692
I'm the one
who's supposed to help you,

27:18.823 --> 27:20.563
to provide for you
and the children,

27:20.694 --> 27:22.087
to protect you
and the children.

27:24.959 --> 27:28.093
Then thank God Henri-Christian
was wi' me this evening

27:28.223 --> 27:29.921
and that he drinks
his mother's milk.

27:30.051 --> 27:31.226
What does that mean?

27:33.228 --> 27:35.535
You think I'd let any harm
come to him?

27:36.405 --> 27:38.451
Well, it's fine job
ye'd do in that state.

27:38.581 --> 27:39.757
You can't protect anyone
when you're drunk!

27:42.585 --> 27:43.761
You're right.

27:47.895 --> 27:49.680
Only I wasn't drunk
when I failed you before.

27:50.985 --> 27:52.334
I can fight for us too.

27:56.512 --> 27:58.906
The burden is not only on you.

27:58.993 --> 28:00.603
I can protect us as well.

28:00.734 --> 28:02.344
Not against men
like Lionel Brown.

28:02.475 --> 28:04.433
Aye, I can.

28:04.564 --> 28:05.870
And I did.

28:09.308 --> 28:12.572
[tense music plays]

28:12.703 --> 28:14.443
Let this be a comfort to ye,
Fergus, for I mean it to be.

28:14.617 --> 28:17.098
♪ ♪

28:17.229 --> 28:18.578
Lionel didn't die.

28:18.752 --> 28:21.450
♪ ♪

28:22.974 --> 28:23.931
I killed him.

28:25.193 --> 28:26.412
What?

28:28.153 --> 28:29.415
What did you say?

28:29.545 --> 28:31.678
He threatened me.

28:31.809 --> 28:33.419
He threatened all of us.

28:33.549 --> 28:36.378
He said he'd burn the house
down over our heads.

28:36.509 --> 28:38.380
[chair clatters]

28:39.251 --> 28:42.950
So I filled a syringe
with water hemlock,

28:43.037 --> 28:44.909
and I stabbed him in the neck.

28:45.083 --> 28:47.520
♪ ♪

28:47.650 --> 28:48.913
You killed him?

28:51.567 --> 28:53.004
I was worried
it would haunt me.

28:54.832 --> 28:55.702
But it doesna.

28:57.748 --> 29:00.489
An evil man is gone,
and no harm will come to us.

29:00.620 --> 29:03.841
I don't need a woman
to protect me!

29:04.015 --> 29:06.974
♪ ♪

29:07.105 --> 29:08.889
But I do need a drink.

29:09.020 --> 29:11.762
[somber music plays]

29:11.936 --> 29:14.677
♪ ♪

29:16.114 --> 29:17.419
Thirsty, are you?

29:29.475 --> 29:30.606
[pitcher clatters]

29:32.304 --> 29:33.827
I hope that's quenched it.

29:33.958 --> 29:37.178
[breathing heavily]

29:37.265 --> 29:39.180
Now leave!

29:39.354 --> 29:41.443
♪ ♪

29:41.574 --> 29:43.750
I said leave!

29:44.620 --> 29:47.058
-I am the man of this house!
-[baby crying]

29:47.145 --> 29:48.842
Well, then you can come back
when you're acting like one.

29:48.929 --> 29:50.888
♪ ♪

29:50.975 --> 29:52.803
[crying continues]

29:52.933 --> 29:55.022
You promised me, Fergus Fraser!

29:55.196 --> 29:56.719
♪ ♪

29:56.850 --> 29:59.592
And I will have a whole man

29:59.722 --> 30:01.594
or none at all.

30:01.768 --> 30:04.510
♪ ♪

30:06.904 --> 30:08.340
[door slams]

30:08.514 --> 30:11.299
♪ ♪

30:16.609 --> 30:19.090
What would you have done
if they'd chosen the poker?

30:19.177 --> 30:20.569
I would let them
have their punishment.

30:22.528 --> 30:24.747
I hope they go home
and tell their parents.

30:24.878 --> 30:26.140
Aye.

30:26.271 --> 30:27.968
On the other hand,
if their parents

30:28.099 --> 30:31.015
think he's demon-born,

30:31.102 --> 30:35.323
I'm his grandsire,
and ye're his granny,

30:35.410 --> 30:36.847
what does that say about us?

30:36.977 --> 30:37.978
[chuckles]

30:41.416 --> 30:43.505
[Lionel] It says you're
of the devil yourself.

30:43.636 --> 30:46.769
[eerie music plays]

30:46.857 --> 30:48.989
[Claire gasping]

30:49.120 --> 30:50.251
What's wrong, Sassenach?

30:51.557 --> 30:53.515
Nothing.

30:53.689 --> 30:56.431
♪ ♪

30:57.476 --> 30:58.390
I, um...

30:58.564 --> 31:01.610
♪ ♪

31:01.741 --> 31:03.917
...I'm going to go downstairs,

31:04.004 --> 31:05.266
look in on Tom.

31:05.440 --> 31:08.182
♪ ♪

31:37.211 --> 31:38.299
[Tom] Mistress Fraser.

31:40.214 --> 31:41.607
[Claire] Mr. Christie.

31:47.004 --> 31:48.788
You're slightly feverish.

31:48.919 --> 31:50.007
Here.

31:51.660 --> 31:53.488
[Tom groaning]

31:53.619 --> 31:54.620
Easy.

32:09.243 --> 32:11.419
Just want to see how
your hand's doing, that's all.

32:15.423 --> 32:17.773
Throbbing a bit.

32:17.904 --> 32:19.036
Keeping me from sleep.

32:24.432 --> 32:27.522
Why do you never wear
a proper kerch or cap?

32:29.611 --> 32:31.135
Why should I?

32:31.222 --> 32:33.920
'Cause every pious
married woman should.

32:34.051 --> 32:38.533
"And every woman
who prayeth or prophesieth

32:38.664 --> 32:42.407
"with her head uncovered
dishonoreth her head.

32:42.537 --> 32:45.366
For that is just
as if she were shaven."

32:45.497 --> 32:47.803
Are we back
to Saint Paul again?

32:47.890 --> 32:49.805
Ever occur to you that man had

32:49.936 --> 32:52.156
quite the bee in his bonnet
about women?

32:52.243 --> 32:54.114
Besides, I'm not praying
right now.

32:54.245 --> 32:55.420
I want to see
how this does overnight

32:55.550 --> 32:57.204
before I risk
prophesying about it.

32:59.250 --> 33:00.338
-It looks like it's doing--
-Your hair.

33:03.558 --> 33:05.038
There's a great deal of it.

33:07.214 --> 33:08.128
There is a great deal of it.

33:09.042 --> 33:10.913
Eh.

33:11.044 --> 33:14.874
You should, um,
move your fingers regularly

33:15.005 --> 33:17.833
to prevent the muscles from
contracting while it's healing.

33:17.964 --> 33:19.313
It will hurt at first,

33:19.444 --> 33:20.967
but you must do it.

33:21.098 --> 33:22.447
Here, let me show you.

33:22.577 --> 33:24.971
If you take your other hand
and you...

33:25.102 --> 33:26.320
[Tom groans]

33:26.451 --> 33:29.280
[Claire]
...stretch out that joint,

33:29.367 --> 33:32.239
you should feel the pull
go down the palm.

33:32.370 --> 33:33.545
That's what's needed.

33:33.675 --> 33:35.721
Here. Try it.

33:40.030 --> 33:41.248
Mr. Christie, are you hungry?

33:42.945 --> 33:44.991
A little, I suppose. Aye.

33:45.122 --> 33:47.863
I'll fetch you something.

33:47.994 --> 33:49.778
You should, uh, keep trying
those exercises for a bit.

33:49.909 --> 33:51.215
Aye.

33:53.652 --> 33:56.437
[tense music plays]

33:56.611 --> 33:59.310
♪ ♪

34:04.793 --> 34:06.273
[sighs]

34:06.404 --> 34:08.667
Oh, hello, cat.

34:08.797 --> 34:11.104
[cat meows]

34:11.235 --> 34:13.193
Don't you be thinking
any of this ham is for you.

34:13.324 --> 34:15.239
[cat purring]

34:15.369 --> 34:18.633
I might be able to rustle up
some milk for you, though.

34:18.720 --> 34:19.982
Here. [smooches]

34:20.157 --> 34:22.942
♪ ♪

34:32.691 --> 34:33.561
You were thirsty.

34:40.655 --> 34:43.310
You should let that rest now.

34:43.441 --> 34:45.443
Don't want the wound
to start bleeding again.

34:50.578 --> 34:51.797
Is there someone else
in the kitchen?

34:53.320 --> 34:54.800
I heard you speaking
to someone.

34:54.930 --> 34:58.108
[laughs] No, it was just the
cat.

34:59.761 --> 35:02.677
And no, he's not my familiar.

35:02.808 --> 35:04.810
It's just a cat.

35:04.940 --> 35:06.899
It's only slightly
less ridiculous talking to him

35:06.986 --> 35:08.727
than talking to myself, is all.

35:08.857 --> 35:12.122
Mm, I told you,
I am an educated man.

35:12.252 --> 35:14.124
I do not think you are a witch.

35:14.950 --> 35:17.214
Oh, you don't?

35:17.344 --> 35:19.564
So don't you believe
in witches?

35:19.694 --> 35:21.609
There are witches
in the Bible, you know.

35:21.740 --> 35:23.698
I did not say that
I do not believe in witches.

35:23.829 --> 35:25.352
I do.

35:25.483 --> 35:26.527
I said I don't think
you are one.

35:28.312 --> 35:29.574
I'm very pleased
to hear that.

35:38.060 --> 35:39.627
I want to apologize to you...

35:41.629 --> 35:42.891
...for my behavior
this morning.

35:44.632 --> 35:45.633
It's quite all right.

35:48.027 --> 35:51.944
I can see how the idea
of being put to sleep

35:52.074 --> 35:53.989
might seem peculiar.

35:54.076 --> 35:55.730
I don't mean that.

35:56.862 --> 36:00.735
I meant that... I could not
keep myself still.

36:00.866 --> 36:02.781
I wouldn't expect anyone
to keep still

36:02.911 --> 36:04.478
while I cut into their hand.

36:04.609 --> 36:06.132
Not even your husband?

36:07.002 --> 36:09.657
He said you'd healed
his hand for him.

36:09.788 --> 36:11.616
He didn't squirm when you
did it, though, did he?

36:14.227 --> 36:16.055
Everyone's different.

36:16.186 --> 36:19.450
You wouldn't expect any man
to do as well as him.

36:19.580 --> 36:20.973
I know that.

36:21.103 --> 36:23.715
That's not what I meant.

36:23.845 --> 36:26.979
Yeah, I've stitched wounds
and set bones

36:27.109 --> 36:28.807
for many men.

36:28.937 --> 36:31.723
Nearly all the Highlanders.

36:31.810 --> 36:33.028
They were terribly brave
about it.

36:39.861 --> 36:42.212
You know your husband bears
the stripes of flogging.

36:43.691 --> 36:44.997
Yes, of course.

36:45.127 --> 36:46.955
Oh, but do you know why?

36:47.086 --> 36:49.044
Yes, I do.

36:49.131 --> 36:50.307
But you don't.

36:50.437 --> 36:53.092
Not all of them, it's true.

36:53.179 --> 36:55.964
He arrived at Ardsmuir
with a great many stripes.

36:56.051 --> 36:58.924
But-but I know he earned more

36:59.054 --> 37:00.099
while we were
in prison together.

37:02.144 --> 37:04.016
He claimed a bit of tartan.

37:05.713 --> 37:06.975
It was forbidden.

37:07.106 --> 37:08.542
Do you know why?

37:08.673 --> 37:11.415
It wasn't his.

37:11.545 --> 37:12.372
An old man's.

37:14.069 --> 37:18.596
It was an act
of extraordinary courage.

37:21.599 --> 37:23.253
Incomprehensible.

37:23.383 --> 37:24.776
How he could do it, you mean?

37:24.906 --> 37:27.300
Not how. Why.

37:29.563 --> 37:31.348
Well, he would do anything
to protect one of his men.

37:34.525 --> 37:38.833
Is that why today--
his presence here...

37:38.964 --> 37:40.182
does he think
I'm one of his men?

37:42.228 --> 37:44.578
'Cause I assure you, I am not.

37:44.709 --> 37:47.277
I'm sure he doesn't.

37:47.364 --> 37:49.757
I'm sure it was simply
an act of kindness.

37:49.888 --> 37:52.543
And he would do the same
for any stranger,

37:52.673 --> 37:53.718
as you would yourself,
wouldn't you?

37:55.502 --> 37:56.416
Mm.

37:59.767 --> 38:01.987
[sighs]

38:02.074 --> 38:03.554
[grunts]

38:13.607 --> 38:14.391
[Claire]
Good night, Mr. Christie.

38:14.521 --> 38:15.348
Mm.

38:32.670 --> 38:33.801
How was Tom?

38:38.458 --> 38:42.027
He-he seems to be doing
quite well, actually.

38:46.292 --> 38:47.902
Is Tom afraid of women?

38:50.209 --> 38:53.473
Or...

38:53.604 --> 38:56.998
was he just afraid
of sinning, I suppose?

38:58.173 --> 39:00.654
He seemed so uncomfortable
with me touching his hand

39:00.785 --> 39:03.483
or-or touching him
at all, really.

39:03.614 --> 39:06.617
I was like that, too,
after Ardsmuir.

39:09.489 --> 39:12.840
It was shocking to be touched,
especially by a woman.

39:12.971 --> 39:14.799
[solemn music plays]

39:14.886 --> 39:18.368
It would be weeks, ye ken,

39:18.455 --> 39:19.847
we wouldn't think of it.

39:19.934 --> 39:21.675
♪ ♪

39:21.806 --> 39:25.331
We were always starved, cold,

39:25.462 --> 39:28.334
worn to the bone.

39:28.465 --> 39:29.770
Every now and then,
something would change.

39:29.901 --> 39:34.209
The fog of exhaustion
would lift.

39:34.296 --> 39:36.995
A story someone told, maybe,

39:37.125 --> 39:39.780
a letter from someone's wife
or sister.

39:39.954 --> 39:41.739
♪ ♪

39:41.869 --> 39:45.307
Sometimes it came from nowhere.

39:45.395 --> 39:50.051
But you'd wake to it
in the night,

39:50.138 --> 39:53.533
in the dark,

39:53.664 --> 39:58.146
like the smell of a woman
lying next to you.

39:58.277 --> 40:00.322
Memory...

40:00.453 --> 40:03.369
longing...

40:03.500 --> 40:04.588
need.

40:04.762 --> 40:06.851
♪ ♪

40:06.981 --> 40:10.202
Some men would
reach out to another,

40:10.332 --> 40:14.032
sometimes to be rebuffed
by shouts or blows,

40:14.162 --> 40:15.947
sometimes not.

40:16.121 --> 40:18.340
♪ ♪

40:18.471 --> 40:20.342
And Tom?

40:20.473 --> 40:23.955
No. Hmm. Tom turned inward.

40:24.129 --> 40:25.739
♪ ♪

40:25.826 --> 40:27.741
I was lucky.

40:27.872 --> 40:29.613
You helped pull me back
from the darkness.

40:29.787 --> 40:32.485
♪ ♪

40:33.660 --> 40:37.795
He was already at Ardsmuir

40:37.925 --> 40:40.624
when you arrived, wasn't he?

40:40.711 --> 40:43.844
And then you both left
at the same time.

40:44.018 --> 40:45.846
♪ ♪

40:45.977 --> 40:48.588
When the prison
was closed, aye.

40:48.719 --> 40:50.634
Tom was transported
to the colonies

40:50.764 --> 40:52.549
to serve his indenture.

40:52.679 --> 40:53.811
Why?

40:53.898 --> 40:56.248
Malva...

40:56.378 --> 40:59.773
she would be 18, wouldn't she?

40:59.947 --> 41:01.906
♪ ♪

41:02.036 --> 41:04.169
Wouldn't Tom
have still been at Ardsmuir

41:04.299 --> 41:07.128
when she was conceived?

41:07.259 --> 41:11.481
Maybe he remarried when he
arrived in the colonies.

41:11.611 --> 41:13.091
[Claire] Hmm.

41:13.265 --> 41:16.529
♪ ♪

41:17.225 --> 41:20.402
Did any of the men
ever touch you?

41:20.533 --> 41:22.622
No.

41:22.753 --> 41:24.755
No one would ever think
to touch me.

41:24.842 --> 41:26.800
I was their chief.

41:26.931 --> 41:28.672
They loved me.

41:28.759 --> 41:30.108
None would think
ever to touch me.

41:30.282 --> 41:32.414
♪ ♪

41:32.502 --> 41:34.112
Did you ever want them to?

41:34.199 --> 41:36.549
No.

41:36.680 --> 41:39.552
I hungered
for the touch of a hand.

41:39.639 --> 41:42.076
Only that.

41:42.207 --> 41:44.426
I longed for it.

41:44.557 --> 41:47.604
More than food,
more than sleep.

41:47.778 --> 41:49.780
♪ ♪

41:49.910 --> 41:51.782
Though I longed
most desperately for sleep,

41:51.912 --> 41:56.221
for-not only for the sake
of tiredness,

41:56.351 --> 42:00.225
but when I slept...
I dreamt of you.

42:00.399 --> 42:03.141
♪ ♪

42:19.940 --> 42:21.768
My brother tells me
you're a fearsome hunter.

42:21.899 --> 42:24.379
[soft music plays]

42:24.466 --> 42:27.078
Aye. I suppose.

42:27.208 --> 42:28.819
Keeps me well fed.

42:28.949 --> 42:30.385
[Malva chuckles]

42:30.516 --> 42:32.387
As I used to say
when my father would ask me

42:32.518 --> 42:36.261
what I must do to avoid
the fiery pits of hell,

42:36.391 --> 42:38.742
"Be sure to eat well,
and take good care not to die."

42:38.872 --> 42:40.526
[laughs]

42:42.267 --> 42:44.878
Well, your father is, uh...

42:47.577 --> 42:49.666
Must be difficult
to live with the burden

42:49.796 --> 42:51.711
of such high expectations.

42:51.798 --> 42:54.148
Hmm.

42:54.279 --> 42:56.586
And sometimes I think
people make mistakes

42:56.716 --> 42:59.240
and do the wrong thing,

42:59.371 --> 43:00.502
but perhaps
for the right reasons.

43:10.121 --> 43:12.689
I suppose your uncle
doesn't mind much what you do.

43:12.819 --> 43:14.952
That you've markings
on your face

43:15.082 --> 43:18.695
or that you're not...
a Christian, I suppose?

43:18.825 --> 43:19.783
Hmm.

43:22.002 --> 43:26.833
No, I dinna ken what I am
or what I believe.

43:26.964 --> 43:28.269
But I'll always have a home
with Uncle Jamie.

43:30.489 --> 43:33.448
And he'd give me the coat
off his back if I asked him.

43:33.535 --> 43:35.973
-Or wi'out askin', either.
-[Malva] Hmm.

43:36.103 --> 43:38.149
He loves you
as his own son, then.

43:38.236 --> 43:40.325
Aye.

43:40.455 --> 43:43.023
He's given me some land
of my own to farm.

43:43.154 --> 43:44.895
Must you pay him rent
for Quarter Day?

43:44.982 --> 43:47.201
No, not yet.
Havena been farmin'.

43:51.031 --> 43:53.468
You know, I dinna ken
if my place is here,

43:53.555 --> 43:55.993
with them, or for how long.

43:56.123 --> 43:57.516
Where else would it be?

44:00.954 --> 44:03.348
He must think you
very worthy and capable.

44:05.350 --> 44:06.394
Aye.

44:08.266 --> 44:09.354
Man o' worth.

44:10.181 --> 44:11.182
[Malva chuckles]

44:14.185 --> 44:17.057
[soft music plays]

44:17.188 --> 44:18.319
Do they mean something?

44:18.493 --> 44:19.930
♪ ♪

44:20.017 --> 44:22.497
That I've done much
that I'm proud of

44:22.628 --> 44:23.760
and much that I regret.

44:23.934 --> 44:25.370
♪ ♪

44:25.500 --> 44:27.938
-You've lived, then.
-I have.

44:28.112 --> 44:31.028
♪ ♪

44:31.158 --> 44:33.987
There's no sin in that,
I suppose.

44:34.118 --> 44:36.076
No.

44:36.250 --> 44:38.165
♪ ♪

44:38.296 --> 44:39.471
None at all.

44:39.645 --> 44:42.430
♪ ♪

44:47.827 --> 44:50.351
[Claire] What has it been,
a week now?

44:51.570 --> 44:53.441
Oh, that's healing nicely.

44:53.572 --> 44:54.921
Good.

44:55.052 --> 44:55.966
You've been doing
your exercises.

44:56.096 --> 44:57.010
Yes.

44:58.925 --> 44:59.752
Yes.

45:01.798 --> 45:03.843
I look forward to having
its use returned to me.

45:03.974 --> 45:04.975
[Claire] Hmm.

45:12.243 --> 45:15.855
I've been having
trouble sleeping,

45:15.986 --> 45:17.770
so I come down
and read for a bit.

45:17.901 --> 45:20.294
-I find it helps.
-Mm.

45:20.425 --> 45:21.165
Do you read novels?

45:22.949 --> 45:24.951
Uh, yes.

45:25.082 --> 45:26.170
Have you read Tom Jonesbefore?

45:26.257 --> 45:28.433
No.

45:28.563 --> 45:31.436
My wife, she read novels.

45:31.566 --> 45:33.655
But I did not approve of it.

45:33.786 --> 45:34.656
Then.

45:36.397 --> 45:37.355
I threw them all away.

45:39.574 --> 45:41.707
Can't imagine she was
very pleased about that.

45:41.838 --> 45:43.013
She was not.

45:44.754 --> 45:46.407
So what changed your mind?

45:46.538 --> 45:47.365
Ardsmuir.

45:49.323 --> 45:52.196
You know, we had no books there,

45:52.326 --> 45:55.068
but Mr. Fraser was accustomed

45:55.199 --> 45:57.288
to recount the stories
he had read

45:57.418 --> 45:58.724
to the other prisoners.

45:58.855 --> 46:01.988
Not Tom Jonesbut others.

46:02.119 --> 46:05.731
And I saw that fiction
was perhaps not,

46:05.862 --> 46:07.298
as I had thought,

46:07.428 --> 46:10.562
merely an inducement
of idleness

46:10.692 --> 46:14.827
and wicked fancy,
a confection of lies.

46:15.610 --> 46:19.136
Surely there's a difference
between lying

46:19.266 --> 46:21.312
and telling a distracting tale.

46:21.442 --> 46:23.575
[Tom] Oh, it was distraction,
to be sure.

46:23.662 --> 46:27.100
In such conditions,
distraction is, uh, not evil,

46:27.231 --> 46:29.450
while it is, of course,
more desirable

46:29.581 --> 46:32.105
to escape into prayer.

46:32.236 --> 46:34.064
Of course.

46:34.891 --> 46:38.198
But...
it drew the men together.

46:40.070 --> 46:42.376
You would not think
that such men--

46:42.463 --> 46:46.250
crofters, Highlanders--
would find themselves

46:46.380 --> 46:49.079
in sympathy
with such situations.

46:50.863 --> 46:53.518
They were...

46:53.648 --> 46:56.173
they were starved, cold,

46:56.260 --> 46:59.002
covered in sores,
separated from their families,

46:59.132 --> 47:01.134
yet they could take comfort

47:01.221 --> 47:04.616
in never having suffered
such vicissitudes

47:04.746 --> 47:08.315
as had befallen
these imaginary beings.

47:10.230 --> 47:12.406
Would you like to borrow it?

47:12.493 --> 47:14.234
Oh, no, no, I couldn't.

47:14.365 --> 47:17.803
Please. I insist.

47:17.934 --> 47:20.197
It will be
a good distraction for you.

47:20.327 --> 47:22.764
And I will come
and retrieve it in a few days

47:22.895 --> 47:24.505
when I come
to check on your hand.

47:27.813 --> 47:31.991
Well, then, uh,
I must thank you.

47:37.823 --> 47:40.739
I... meant to say

47:40.870 --> 47:43.307
that Richard Brown

47:43.437 --> 47:46.484
came by our settlement
this morning.

47:46.614 --> 47:49.400
He offered us the protection
of his committee of safety,

47:49.530 --> 47:51.576
should we have the need of it.

47:51.706 --> 47:52.664
I hope you refused him.

47:53.708 --> 47:55.536
That man is...

47:55.623 --> 47:57.451
he's not to be trusted.

47:57.538 --> 48:00.106
-[tense music plays]
-[knock at door]

48:00.280 --> 48:03.066
♪ ♪

48:13.859 --> 48:16.470
Please, come in.

48:16.644 --> 48:19.430
♪ ♪

48:27.655 --> 48:29.179
Good day, lass.

48:29.309 --> 48:32.878
Oh, Mr. Fraser,
you startled me.

48:32.965 --> 48:34.271
My father is fond of mushrooms,

48:34.401 --> 48:36.273
so I was looking for wood ears.

48:36.360 --> 48:37.622
[Jamie] What will yer father
do when ye've wed

48:37.752 --> 48:39.102
and left his house?

48:39.232 --> 48:41.931
He'll need someone
to do for him, I expect.

48:42.061 --> 48:45.064
I dinna mean to be wed
anytime soon, sir.

48:45.195 --> 48:46.718
We'll manage well enough.

48:46.848 --> 48:48.328
No?

48:48.415 --> 48:50.461
Surely ye've suitors.

48:50.591 --> 48:53.507
The lads swoon after you
in droves; I've seen them.

48:54.465 --> 48:55.857
Please, sir, ye'll say
no such thing to my father.

48:57.207 --> 48:58.817
I willna.

48:58.948 --> 48:59.861
I was only teasing, lass.

49:00.950 --> 49:03.126
[both chuckle softly]

49:03.256 --> 49:05.041
Is your father so fierce, then?

49:05.998 --> 49:08.566
-I thought you knew him, sir.
-I did.

49:09.567 --> 49:12.178
I'm getting acquainted
with him again.

49:15.007 --> 49:16.704
Have ye enough wood ears there?

49:16.791 --> 49:20.404
I saw a great many yesterday
up near the green spring.

49:22.058 --> 49:23.146
I'm going that way.
I could show ye.

49:24.495 --> 49:25.713
You're very kind.

49:27.672 --> 49:30.066
Thank you.

49:31.284 --> 49:33.591
Your brother, Allan, will
leave home, too, I suppose.

49:33.678 --> 49:36.159
Maybe go down the coast.

49:36.246 --> 49:38.204
I ken he's not
a farmer at heart, is he?

49:38.335 --> 49:41.512
No, he's not.
He grew up in Edinburgh.

49:41.642 --> 49:43.383
You have the same mother,
your brother and you?

49:43.470 --> 49:44.776
Of course.

49:44.906 --> 49:47.561
Born in Scotland? Or here?

49:47.648 --> 49:49.433
Am I such a curiosity
to you, sir?

49:52.349 --> 49:53.872
'Twas Scotland.

49:54.003 --> 49:56.440
But I dinna much remember it.

49:56.570 --> 49:57.658
Some say this place
is like it, though.

49:57.789 --> 49:59.225
Do you think so?

49:59.356 --> 50:01.184
Something like it.

50:01.314 --> 50:03.403
Some parts.

50:03.490 --> 50:06.232
The Great Glen, the forest.

50:06.363 --> 50:07.973
-Mm.
-Aye.

50:08.104 --> 50:09.540
It's very much like this.

50:09.714 --> 50:12.108
♪ ♪

50:12.238 --> 50:15.763
But there is no peat,
o' course.

50:15.937 --> 50:18.897
♪ ♪

50:19.028 --> 50:20.725
-No heather.
-Mm.

50:20.855 --> 50:21.900
That's the biggest difference.

50:22.074 --> 50:24.990
♪ ♪

50:25.121 --> 50:27.993
The mountains...
[continues indistinctly]

50:28.080 --> 50:30.909
♪ ♪

50:33.651 --> 50:36.436
[haunting music plays]

50:36.610 --> 50:39.352
♪ ♪

51:15.997 --> 51:18.870
[indistinct chatter]

51:19.000 --> 51:22.221
[lively music plays]

51:22.352 --> 51:24.484
[Lizzie] Here we are again,
Quarter Day.

51:24.571 --> 51:27.052
Thank you, Miss Wemyss.

51:27.139 --> 51:28.358
I must drink this
before Mr. Christie sees

51:28.488 --> 51:30.142
and chastens me.

51:30.273 --> 51:32.623
What auld Tom doesna ken
willna hurt him.

51:32.753 --> 51:34.842
Lang may yer lum reek.
Slàinte mhath.

51:34.973 --> 51:37.323
Slàinte mhath.

51:37.410 --> 51:39.804
You sure you dinna need
any help, Miss Wemyss?

51:39.934 --> 51:42.241
Kezzie and I could pass
some of that ale round.

51:42.372 --> 51:44.896
Oh, aye, as though
every cup I give ye

51:45.026 --> 51:46.550
wouldna go straight
down yer own two gullets.

51:46.680 --> 51:48.291
[chuckles]

51:48.421 --> 51:50.336
I'm no fool, Josiah Beardsley.

51:50.423 --> 51:52.730
We'll keep watch, then.

51:52.860 --> 51:54.775
Make sure no one
steals a sip uninvited.

51:55.385 --> 51:56.908
If you want to be helpful,

51:57.038 --> 51:58.344
go and fetch me
another barrel of ale.

51:58.518 --> 52:01.086
♪ ♪

52:03.871 --> 52:04.829
Good health.

52:07.179 --> 52:09.094
It's good to get a rest
from the children.

52:09.225 --> 52:11.052
Mm, Mrs. Bug was happy
to watch 'em.

52:11.227 --> 52:14.012
♪ ♪

52:15.274 --> 52:16.754
[whispering] The state of him.

52:16.884 --> 52:18.538
Come. Come.

52:18.625 --> 52:21.367
♪ ♪

52:23.935 --> 52:24.979
[Roger] Padraic MacNeill.

52:25.066 --> 52:27.330
Ah. Well done, sir.

52:27.417 --> 52:28.287
Keep this up,
and ye'll have enough

52:28.374 --> 52:30.768
to feed a family of five.

52:30.898 --> 52:32.770
Now, where are yer
two wee scamps?

52:32.900 --> 52:34.641
They'll be off
making mischief somewhere.

52:34.772 --> 52:36.556
Gone lookin' for sweetmeats,
no doubt.

52:41.909 --> 52:43.911
Evan Lindsay.
Ye've had a good year.

52:44.042 --> 52:46.262
Aye, Mac Dubh.
My crops have been blessed.

52:46.349 --> 52:47.741
Time the good Lord
blessed ye with a wife

52:47.828 --> 52:49.439
to spend all that money on.

52:49.569 --> 52:51.049
Perhaps He'll introduce me
to yer sister,

52:51.180 --> 52:52.093
since ye're spoken for.

52:52.224 --> 52:54.183
Careful now.

52:54.313 --> 52:55.706
She's far too young
for the likes of ye.

52:55.836 --> 52:57.969
And she's in Scotland, forbye.

52:58.099 --> 52:59.492
-[Evan] Oh, yeah.
-[Marsali chuckles]

52:59.623 --> 53:01.233
[Evan] You look nice.

53:01.407 --> 53:04.628
♪ ♪

53:04.715 --> 53:06.238
I think we should set Evan up
with Lizzie.

53:06.369 --> 53:07.631
What do you think?

53:07.761 --> 53:09.459
[Roger chuckles]

53:09.589 --> 53:12.157
If he can get past Josiah
and Kezzie Beardsley, that is.

53:12.288 --> 53:13.811
What do you mean?

53:14.986 --> 53:16.422
You haven't noticed?

53:17.771 --> 53:19.512
They're very protective.

53:19.643 --> 53:20.687
Your mother says that
they follow Lizzie around

53:20.818 --> 53:22.428
like two puppies.

53:22.559 --> 53:23.603
More like two wolves.

53:24.648 --> 53:26.040
There you go.

53:26.171 --> 53:28.129
They've just gone
to get some more.

53:28.260 --> 53:30.480
[Claire] I'll send over
a recipe if you'd like.

53:30.610 --> 53:33.222
I'll get Mrs.-Mrs. Crombie
to have a look at that.

53:33.309 --> 53:34.658
[Lizzie] There's a wee bit
left for you.

53:34.745 --> 53:37.400
[indistinct chatter]

53:44.972 --> 53:46.626
Whatever you want to say to me,

53:46.757 --> 53:47.845
you might as well say it.

53:49.760 --> 53:51.327
You've been staring at me
all morning.

53:52.980 --> 53:54.721
Staring at me
like you stare at my son.

53:54.852 --> 53:56.593
[tense music plays]

53:56.680 --> 53:59.596
Have you never seen a man
with one hand before?

53:59.726 --> 54:01.075
Or a dwarf?

54:01.250 --> 54:04.035
♪ ♪

54:06.733 --> 54:08.082
Are we so hideous?

54:08.213 --> 54:09.823
Hideously drunk.

54:11.085 --> 54:13.174
But as to your son,

54:13.305 --> 54:14.959
I think "grotesque"
may be the word.

54:15.133 --> 54:16.482
♪ ♪

54:16.613 --> 54:18.876
But you tell us...

54:19.006 --> 54:20.834
if you can bear to look at him
yourself.

54:21.226 --> 54:23.010
-Oh!
-Hey!

54:23.141 --> 54:24.011
-[blows landing]
-[grunting]

54:24.098 --> 54:26.362
-Fergus!
-Fergus!

54:26.449 --> 54:29.234
♪ ♪

54:30.322 --> 54:32.411
This madman attacked me!

54:32.542 --> 54:33.630
[Claire] Did you see
what happened?

54:33.717 --> 54:35.458
It was her fault, mostly.

54:35.588 --> 54:37.155
She shouldna ha' said
what she did about the bairn.

54:37.286 --> 54:38.852
I saw him throw whisky
in her face.

54:38.983 --> 54:40.637
Oh, surely
it's a curse from God

54:40.767 --> 54:42.378
for a child to look that way!

54:42.465 --> 54:44.249
How dare you?

54:44.336 --> 54:46.382
Drink is the devil's juice.

54:46.512 --> 54:49.341
Isn't that what you
always say, Mr. Christie?

54:49.472 --> 54:52.866
Well, the lad's father's
barely seen without a cup.

54:52.997 --> 54:55.304
The Frasers have opened
their doors to us.

54:55.434 --> 54:57.480
We will respect them
in the eyes of the Lord,

54:57.610 --> 55:00.091
with pity...

55:00.221 --> 55:01.353
and kindness.

55:01.527 --> 55:04.182
♪ ♪

55:04.313 --> 55:06.576
[Fergus speaking French]

55:06.663 --> 55:08.273
Mr. MacGregor.

55:08.404 --> 55:10.884
[dramatic music plays]

55:11.015 --> 55:12.799
What's happened?

55:12.973 --> 55:16.237
♪ ♪

55:16.368 --> 55:18.762
[Roger] As we all settle
in this new land,

55:18.849 --> 55:22.766
so far from the soil
in which many of us were born,

55:22.896 --> 55:24.768
I want to reflect on the words

55:24.855 --> 55:28.685
"thou shalt love
they neighbor as thyself."

55:28.815 --> 55:33.516
I feel compelled to tell
a story about a helpless child

55:33.646 --> 55:36.867
who was floated down a river
in a basket.

55:36.954 --> 55:39.696
[tense music plays]

55:39.870 --> 55:42.568
♪ ♪

55:43.656 --> 55:44.614
His name was Moses.

55:44.788 --> 55:47.965
♪ ♪

55:48.095 --> 55:49.967
Pharaoh ordered
that all Hebrew boys

55:50.097 --> 55:53.187
be thrown into the Nile
and drowned,

55:53.318 --> 55:55.625
an edict
that nearly killed the child

55:55.755 --> 55:57.844
that would later lead
God's people to freedom.

55:58.018 --> 56:00.804
♪ ♪

56:06.592 --> 56:08.202
[sharp slap]

56:08.289 --> 56:10.379
It was fear
that made him do it.

56:10.553 --> 56:13.382
♪ ♪

56:23.087 --> 56:25.263
For months,
Moses' mother kept him hidden,

56:25.394 --> 56:27.004
risking her own life,

56:27.134 --> 56:30.224
until he was too big to hide.

56:30.355 --> 56:33.314
She placed him in a basket

56:33.445 --> 56:37.754
in the River Nile and prayed.

56:37.841 --> 56:40.670
She entrusted him to God,

56:40.757 --> 56:42.759
in spite of her fear.

56:42.846 --> 56:45.544
♪ ♪

56:56.555 --> 56:58.035
Many of you are parents.

57:00.559 --> 57:02.213
To what lengths would you go

57:02.343 --> 57:03.997
to protect
your innocent children?

57:04.084 --> 57:06.347
♪ ♪

57:06.478 --> 57:08.437
You never know what you'll
be willing to do until--

57:08.611 --> 57:11.352
♪ ♪

57:12.223 --> 57:13.746
Fergus!

57:13.877 --> 57:16.619
[dramatic music plays]

57:16.793 --> 57:19.926
♪ ♪

57:20.231 --> 57:22.015
No, milord. Let me be.

57:22.189 --> 57:24.931
♪ ♪

57:26.759 --> 57:27.673
No!

57:28.457 --> 57:31.242
♪ ♪

57:36.943 --> 57:39.424
Let me die.
This is the only way.

57:40.164 --> 57:41.861
Marsali and the children
need you.

57:41.992 --> 57:44.342
This is for them.

57:44.473 --> 57:46.866
Marsali can marry again,

57:46.997 --> 57:50.000
find a man who can provide
for her and the children,

57:50.130 --> 57:52.829
protect Henri-Christian.

57:52.959 --> 57:53.873
I cannot.

57:54.004 --> 57:55.571
You can.

57:56.136 --> 57:57.268
[Fergus] You know damn well
I can't.

57:58.835 --> 58:01.141
Roger saved him.

58:01.272 --> 58:03.927
You protect him.

58:04.057 --> 58:06.582
I'm nothing.

58:06.712 --> 58:08.584
I'm useless.

58:08.714 --> 58:09.933
Useless?

58:10.020 --> 58:12.413
♪ ♪

58:12.544 --> 58:15.721
You kept this family together
while I was at Ardsmuir.

58:15.895 --> 58:17.636
♪ ♪

58:17.723 --> 58:18.724
You helped me at my print shop

58:18.855 --> 58:21.031
when I was grieving for Claire.

58:21.205 --> 58:22.728
♪ ♪

58:22.859 --> 58:25.557
With this one hand,

58:25.688 --> 58:29.343
you made some of the finest
whisky ever passed my lips.

58:31.171 --> 58:32.695
You will do so again.

58:32.869 --> 58:35.001
♪ ♪

58:35.088 --> 58:37.830
Ye're the only one
who can show yer son

58:37.961 --> 58:42.313
what a "useless" man
like ye can achieve

58:42.443 --> 58:44.315
and how proud
he can make his father.

58:44.402 --> 58:45.969
♪ ♪

58:46.056 --> 58:47.274
Ye dinna ken.

58:47.361 --> 58:48.711
But it's you, not what you do

58:48.841 --> 58:52.584
or... give or provide.

58:52.758 --> 58:55.021
♪ ♪

58:55.152 --> 58:56.109
It's you we need...

58:56.283 --> 58:59.069
♪ ♪

59:00.113 --> 59:01.811
...to come home.

59:01.898 --> 59:06.032
[speaking French]

59:06.206 --> 59:09.079
♪ ♪

59:09.209 --> 59:11.472
I'm not who I once was, milord.

59:15.172 --> 59:16.782
I don't know
if I can be that man again.

59:18.349 --> 59:19.611
You can.

59:30.883 --> 59:32.058
You will.

59:32.189 --> 59:35.061
[warm music]

59:35.235 --> 59:37.977
♪ ♪

59:48.597 --> 59:51.425
♪ ♪

1:00:00.217 --> 1:00:02.132
[Fergus]
I'm sorry. Never again.

1:00:02.306 --> 1:00:05.091
♪ ♪

1:00:09.226 --> 1:00:12.011
[baby cooing]

1:00:12.185 --> 1:00:14.971
♪ ♪

1:00:33.946 --> 1:00:35.818
Major MacDonald.

1:00:35.948 --> 1:00:37.341
[McDonald]
Mr. Fraser, Mistress Fraser.

1:00:37.471 --> 1:00:38.995
I come bearing gifts.

1:00:39.125 --> 1:00:40.866
Your letter requesting guns
was well-received.

1:00:45.044 --> 1:00:47.351
And it appears
the loyalty and readiness

1:00:47.438 --> 1:00:49.788
of the Snowbird Cherokee

1:00:49.919 --> 1:00:51.181
couldn't have come
at a better time.

1:00:55.533 --> 1:00:58.057
[Claire] The Boston Tea Party.

1:00:58.188 --> 1:00:59.624
[McDonald] Oh, so you've heard.

1:00:59.755 --> 1:01:01.582
An inconvenience, certainly.

1:01:01.713 --> 1:01:02.975
Imagine the King will view it

1:01:03.106 --> 1:01:04.890
as an act
of outright aggression.

1:01:05.630 --> 1:01:06.675
Where would you like them?

1:01:09.068 --> 1:01:13.203
We'll, uh, store them
in the corncrib for now.

1:01:13.333 --> 1:01:16.075
[tense music plays]

1:01:16.249 --> 1:01:18.991
♪ ♪

1:01:31.351 --> 1:01:32.396
What does it mean, Sassenach?

1:01:34.703 --> 1:01:37.009
It's starting.

1:01:37.140 --> 1:01:39.403
The storm, the war...

1:01:39.533 --> 1:01:41.405
it's almost here.

1:01:41.492 --> 1:01:44.190
[dramatic music plays]

1:01:44.364 --> 1:01:47.106
♪ ♪
